>>41675656
To your latter point there, I've noticed an unexpected tolerance... and subtle encouragement in writing spaces, particularly academia, toward interspecial relationships in genre fiction. This is just my experience, mind you. For those who work in – or are at least advanced with – the artistry of language, genre fiction provides an acceptable (and even enticing) epistemological egress from conventional writing subjects, standards, and tropes. There's a certain pedagogic advantage to writing interspecies relations, and romances with non-human/human characters, that can be more digestibly paralleled with rl situations & circumstances over those mirrored with only human characters. I somewhat feel that the prevalence of anthropomorphic characters in Golden Age media is largely why Late-'80s and '90s millennials were/are the closest we've come, as a species, to a post-racial generation any time before (and especially after) the turn of the century. Media pivoted away from non-human characters after Y2K super hard, and I think that made it waaay too easy to twist popular modes of escapism - like shows and books - into commercial platforms for sociopolitical proselytizing over, say, tacitly engendering fictional narratives with universally applicable moral axioms.
People (consumers) are waxing scrupulous of corporate/political, top-down social engineering efforts in media today because of the swarm of literallywho writers who flew in out of nowhere, in force & funding, with flagrantly flippant & salaciously shoddy narratives that, upon scrutiny, never assay their authors' life experiences. There's no authenticity or "human spark" to them because the narratives have neither reflection, experience, nor even careful research from their authors to draw or build upon.
